{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/install-and-configure-opencv-4-2-0-in-windows-10-vc-d132c52063a1", "time": 1683006048.8773062, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/install-and-configure-opencv-4-2-0-in-windows-10-vc-d132c52063a1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Install and configure OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 \u2014 VC++ | by Aymane Hachcham | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Install and configure OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 \u2014 VC++", "description": "This post will guide you through all the steps for installing and configuring OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 (64-bit) within 2 different environments: I will focus here on OpenCV for Visual Studio with\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/p/7a7386ae024/edit", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/vs/community/", "anchor_text": "Visual Studio 2019", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://opencv.org/", "anchor_text": "https://opencv.org/", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://docs.opencv.org/2.4/doc/tutorials/introduction/windows_visual_studio_Opencv/windows_visual_studio_Opencv.html", "anchor_text": "OpenCV official guide", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["This post will guide you through all the steps for installing and configuring OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 (64-bit) within 2 different environments:", "I will focus here on OpenCV for Visual Studio with C++, the other tutorial part for python and Anaconda can be found here.", "Note: To follow along with the tutorial, I will assume that you already have Visual Studio 2019 installed. If not, please feel free to install these tools before continuing to read further.", "All the required steps for setting up OpenCV for a Visual C++ development.", "Open your Visual Studio Installer tool and add C++ for desktop development as a workload to your current Visual Studio IDE version. This step is essential since you can not use OpenCV in VS without all the C++ required libraries.", "Download OpenCV 4.2.0 latest stable release (opencv-4.2.0-vc14_vc15.exe) for Windows platform. Go to the official OpenCV website: https://opencv.org/ -> Resources -> Releases and click on the Windows platform. You will be redirected to SourceForge and download will automatically start.", "Before running the download .exe file, go to your C:\\ folder and add a new folder named opencv-4.2.0. Run the installer and extract the zip file to the opencv-4.2.0 folder newly created.", "Once OpenCV is correctly installed in your folder, you now have to add the binaries C:\\OpenCV-4.2.0\\opencv\\build\\x64\\vc15\\bin to your system path, so you can have access to OpenCV executables easily through your command line.", "Open Visual Studio 2019, choose to create a new project and go for the C++ Console App template.", "Once the project created you should have a layout with a solution explorer to the right having one source file and in the window upper ribbon you should see Debug for x86 platforms, meaning that the project will build and run in debug mode targeting x86 windows architectures.", "There are a bunch of properties to edit before being able to execute any code:", "For the Include directory, you have to add the following path: C:\\OpenCV-4.2.0\\opencv\\build\\include. Do the same for the Library Directories adding this internal path: C:\\OpenCV-4.2.0\\opencv\\build\\x64\\vc15\\lib.", "2. Edit the VC++ project linker with the opencv_world420d.lib OpenCV dynamic library. You will find the DLL (Dynamic Link Library) here: C:\\OpenCV-4.2.0\\opencv\\build\\x64\\vc15\\lib copy the name of the file opencv_world420d.lib and paste it in the dependency box.", "Finally, you can run this demo code in your visual studio IDE to see if it\u2019s all working fine.", "And that\u2019s all, you can now use OpenCV with ease. \ud83d\ude09", "For more install information, visit the OpenCV official guide.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "D